01:14:51.320 --> 01:14:53.070
...and you're a goat tomorrow.

01:14:54.239 --> 01:14:58.868
Now, l didn't come because games
don't mean nothing to me anymore.

01:14:59.411 --> 01:15:00.578
It's not the game.

01:15:01.705 --> 01:15:03.080
It's Skip.

01:15:04.833 --> 01:15:06.709
He's gone for good.

01:15:06.919 --> 01:15:08.252
For good?

01:15:08.587 --> 01:15:11.589
How you know that?
You some kind of fortuneteller?

01:15:12.466 --> 01:15:17.220
I got mad at him and l hit him.
And he ran away.

01:15:17.763 --> 01:15:19.597
Just like you ran away.

01:15:22.100 --> 01:15:23.434
It's only that.

01:15:23.644 --> 01:15:26.354
Skip was never afraid of nothing.

01:15:30.609 --> 01:15:33.277
You think I don't know
what folks are saying?

01:15:33.487 --> 01:15:35.655
That old Dink's a coward?

01:15:35.906 --> 01:15:37.073
Huh?

01:15:37.950 --> 01:15:40.284
Well, l know. And you know what?

01:15:41.578 --> 01:15:45.790
They're right.
I got scared. And l ran.

01:15:48.126 --> 01:15:50.628
You think it's because
I was afraid of dying?

01:15:51.463 --> 01:15:54.465
Because I wished l was dead
plenty of times.

01:15:56.134 --> 01:15:57.969
Then what was it?

01:16:02.474 --> 01:16:05.268
It ain't the dying that's scary, boy.

01:16:08.480 --> 01:16:09.981
It's the killing.

01:16:17.990 --> 01:16:19.031
Now, look.

01:16:19.950 --> 01:16:23.160
That dog ain't lost. You just
need to know where to find him.

01:16:23.328 --> 01:16:26.622
There's gotta be at least
one place around here...

01:16:26.832 --> 01:16:29.625
...that you hadn't thought of
to look at, right?

01:16:43.181 --> 01:16:46.517
Sometimes he gets mad
and says things he doesn't mean.

01:16:49.938 --> 01:16:51.480
He gets it from his mother.

01:16:55.527 --> 01:16:57.570
When I got back from Spain...

01:16:58.864 --> 01:17:00.865
...l got into accounting.

01:17:01.533 --> 01:17:04.368
I figured l could hide this
behind a desk.

01:17:05.537 --> 01:17:09.999
I looked down, and l didn't so much
as look up for a whole year.

01:17:11.168 --> 01:17:13.044
When I finally did...

01:17:14.546 --> 01:17:17.048
...people weren't staring
at me anymore.

01:17:18.717 --> 01:17:20.968
I guess they kind of forgot about it.

01:17:22.262 --> 01:17:25.514
Well, Mr. Morris,
you got a Purple Heart.

01:17:25.724 --> 01:17:27.516
I got a yellow stripe.

01:17:27.726 --> 01:17:30.853
You can trust me.
They don't forget about cowards.

01:17:33.607 --> 01:17:36.525
Well, folks like
to keep things small, Dink.

01:17:36.735 --> 01:17:39.111
Fit you into one pocket or the other.

01:17:39.363 --> 01:17:41.572
Give a man a label...

01:17:41.740 --> 01:17:44.617
...and you never really
need to get to know him.

01:17:46.411 --> 01:17:47.912
My son...

01:17:49.915 --> 01:17:51.916
...he looks up to you, Dink.

01:17:53.585 --> 01:17:57.546
Not because you can run or throw a ball.

01:17:58.590 --> 01:18:00.257
You're his hero...

01:18:00.759 --> 01:18:02.802
...because you're his friend.

01:18:05.931 --> 01:18:07.765
And that's what he needs.

01:18:09.559 --> 01:18:10.810
A friend.

01:18:17.526 --> 01:18:18.651
Well.

01:18:19.444 --> 01:18:20.778
All right, then.

01:18:22.030 --> 01:18:23.072
JACK:
All right.

01:18:31.832 --> 01:18:33.457
Skip!

01:18:35.585 --> 01:18:37.128
Here, Skipper!

01:18:38.630 --> 01:18:39.964
Here, boy!

01:18:40.173 --> 01:18:41.799
Skip!

01:18:42.050 --> 01:18:44.760
[OWL HOOTS]

01:18:45.637 --> 01:18:47.638
Skipper!

01:18:50.684 --> 01:18:52.309
WlLLIE:
Here, boy!

01:18:52.561 --> 01:18:54.562
[CONCRETE SCRAPlNG]

01:19:09.661 --> 01:19:11.370
What the hell?!

01:19:11.621 --> 01:19:14.832
[SKlP GROWLS]

01:19:18.837 --> 01:19:20.421
Skip!

01:19:20.589 --> 01:19:21.630
[SKlP BARKS]

01:19:21.798 --> 01:19:23.007
Damn mutt.

01:19:27.345 --> 01:19:28.345
[SKlP YELPS]

01:19:28.513 --> 01:19:31.682
Skip!

01:19:33.143 --> 01:19:34.310
Skipper!

01:19:34.519 --> 01:19:36.020
Skip!

01:19:36.855 --> 01:19:41.484
What'd you do to him?!
That's my dog! Skip!

01:19:41.902 --> 01:19:44.612
I told you to keep
that damn mutt out of here.

01:19:53.872 --> 01:19:57.041
Why, if it ain't old Dink.
Need a jar of hooch, buddy?

01:19:57.250 --> 01:19:59.502
Millard, fetch a pint for Dink.

01:19:59.711 --> 01:20:02.254
Listen, you boys need
to get on out of here.

01:20:05.675 --> 01:20:06.884
This your buddy?

01:20:07.719 --> 01:20:10.179
You know how much he
and that mongrel cost us?

01:20:10.388 --> 01:20:12.389
I said, you need to get out of here.

01:20:12.641 --> 01:20:15.351
Millard, listen to who's talking.

01:20:15.560 --> 01:20:17.895
Mr. Hitler's best friend.

01:20:18.146 --> 01:20:19.939
[SQUAWKS LlKE A CHlCKEN]

01:20:20.190 --> 01:20:21.857
It's you who better get out of here.

01:20:29.241 --> 01:20:31.575
Get your moonshine
and get out of here.

01:20:31.785 --> 01:20:35.162
And l better never see you
around here again. Got that?

01:20:35.580 --> 01:20:37.164
MlLLARD:
Come on, Junior. Let's go.

01:20:37.457 --> 01:20:38.541
Come on!

01:20:43.547 --> 01:20:44.588
Yeah?

01:20:44.756 --> 01:20:47.299
It's getting too damn popular
around here anyway.

01:20:50.095 --> 01:20:52.555
You better hope that dog lives.

01:21:04.609 --> 01:21:06.777
Skip.

01:21:20.709 --> 01:21:23.836
[WlLLlE CRlES]

01:21:26.423 --> 01:21:27.715
Any word?

01:21:28.216 --> 01:21:29.967
It doesn't look good.

01:21:38.018 --> 01:21:39.310
VET:
Willie.

01:21:39.477 --> 01:21:41.020
Could you come on back, please?

01:21:43.106 --> 01:21:45.357
Do you want someone to go with you?

01:21:49.821 --> 01:21:51.363
He's a big boy.

01:21:51.865 --> 01:21:53.449
He'll be okay.

01:22:14.554 --> 01:22:16.013
Is he gonna die?

01:22:16.264 --> 01:22:17.348
I don't know.

01:22:17.557 --> 01:22:19.475
I've done all I can.

01:22:19.684 --> 01:22:21.685
It's in God's hands now.

01:22:29.694 --> 01:22:31.695
Please don't die, boy.

01:22:34.532 --> 01:22:37.034
What would I do without you?

01:22:38.995 --> 01:22:41.330
You taught me how to play football.

01:22:43.917 --> 01:22:46.043
You helped me meet the guys...

01:22:46.294 --> 01:22:49.296
...and get up enough nerve
to talk to Rivers.

01:22:51.591 --> 01:22:53.842
And understand about Dink.

01:22:58.598 --> 01:23:02.226
I'll never have another
friend like you. Ever.

01:23:09.025 --> 01:23:10.609
[CRIES]

01:23:15.240 --> 01:23:17.324
Skip's gonna be all right.

01:24:02.454 --> 01:24:08.125
[WHlNES]

01:24:09.919 --> 01:24:12.588
Oh, Skip.

01:24:12.797 --> 01:24:13.881
You're all right!

01:24:16.676 --> 01:24:18.302
That's my boy.

01:24:22.140 --> 01:24:23.474
I love you, Skip.

01:24:23.767 --> 01:24:25.476
I knew you'd make it.

01:24:39.824 --> 01:24:42.659
WlLLIE:
I almost lost old Skip that day.

01:24:43.536 --> 01:24:46.830
Even as he was sleeping
on the operating table...

01:24:47.332 --> 01:24:49.416
...he was still teaching me.

01:24:52.003 --> 01:24:53.462
That day...

01:24:54.172 --> 01:24:56.006
...I became a young man.

01:25:01.846 --> 01:25:03.806
Why, in childhood and youth...

01:25:04.015 --> 01:25:07.059
...do we wish time
to pass so quickly?

01:25:08.019 --> 01:25:10.312
We want to grow up so fast.

01:25:10.522 --> 01:25:14.191
Yet as adults,
we wish just the opposite.

01:25:16.444 --> 01:25:17.528
You're a good boy, Skip.

01:25:19.739 --> 01:25:22.366
WlLLIE:
lf, as the authorities often declare...

01:25:22.534 --> 01:25:25.369
...a dog's life in relation
to a human being's...

01:25:25.537 --> 01:25:28.872
...can be calculated by
seven human years to his one...

01:25:29.040 --> 01:25:31.708
...then Skip was an adult
when I was still a boy.

01:25:32.210 --> 01:25:36.880
Sometimes it seemed as if he possessed
the wisdom of a creature...

01:25:37.048 --> 01:25:38.966
...as old as time.

01:26:12.083 --> 01:26:15.002
[CHEERlNG AND CLAPPlNG]

01:26:22.427 --> 01:26:25.596
CROWD:
Waldo, Waldo, Waldo!

01:26:25.889 --> 01:26:28.599
WILLIE: All the lessons you learn
in childhood...

01:26:29.017 --> 01:26:30.934
...kind of come in waves.

01:26:41.321 --> 01:26:44.239
We finally saw Waldo Grace play.

01:26:45.658 --> 01:26:48.452
And play, and play, and play.

01:27:06.971 --> 01:27:09.348
In remembering moments
such as these...

01:27:09.641 --> 01:27:11.975
...I retain the sad, sweet reflection...

01:27:12.185 --> 01:27:17.105
...of being an only child
and having a loyal and loving dog.

01:27:18.149 --> 01:27:20.484
For the struggles of my life...

01:27:20.652 --> 01:27:24.780
...of the dangers, toils and snares
of my childhood hymns...

01:27:25.114 --> 01:27:27.574
...loyalty and love...

01:27:27.992 --> 01:27:29.701
...are the best things of all...

01:27:29.994 --> 01:27:33.330
...and surely the most lasting.

01:27:40.004 --> 01:27:43.507
The day finally arrived for me
to move away from home.

01:27:44.008 --> 01:27:48.637
I was awarded a scholarship
to attend Oxford University in England.

01:27:52.517 --> 01:27:55.519
A long way from Yazoo, Mississippi...

01:27:55.687 --> 01:27:59.022
...and a long way
from my family and friends.

01:28:53.077 --> 01:28:54.911
The dog of your boyhood...

01:28:55.079 --> 01:28:59.416
...teaches you a great deal
about friendship and love and death.

01:29:01.085 --> 01:29:02.919
I was an only child.

01:29:04.422 --> 01:29:06.423
He was an only dog.

01:29:10.386 --> 01:29:12.679
Old Skip was 1 1 ...

01:29:13.264 --> 01:29:15.599
...and feeble with arthritis...

01:29:16.934 --> 01:29:20.729
...but he never lost that
old devilish look in his eye.

01:29:33.409 --> 01:29:35.619
He made my room his own.

01:29:39.248 --> 01:29:42.334
Came across an old photo
of him not long ago.

01:29:43.711 --> 01:29:45.295
His little face...

01:29:45.588 --> 01:29:48.590
...with the long snout sniffing
at something in the air.

01:29:48.800 --> 01:29:51.510
His tail was straight out
and pointing...

01:29:51.844 --> 01:29:56.306
...eyes were flashing
in some momentary excitement.

01:30:17.120 --> 01:30:20.539
He always loved to be rubbed
on the back of his neck.

01:30:20.790 --> 01:30:24.000
And when I did it,
he'd yawn, and he'd stretch...

01:30:24.293 --> 01:30:26.670
...reach out to me with his paws...

01:30:26.838 --> 01:30:29.548
...as if he was trying to embrace me.

01:30:36.681 --> 01:30:40.183
I received a transatlantic
call one day.

01:30:40.685 --> 01:30:42.519
"Skip died"...

01:30:42.854 --> 01:30:44.312
...Daddy said.

01:30:45.690 --> 01:30:48.775
He and my mama wrapped him
in my baseball jacket.

01:30:50.361 --> 01:30:53.822
They buried him out
under our elm tree, they said.

01:30:55.533 --> 01:30:57.701
That wasn't totally true...

01:31:00.705 --> 01:31:02.873
...for he really lay buried...

01:31:03.374 --> 01:31:04.875
...in my heart.

